description.header: Arjun's entry for the Thingiverse #backtoschool Challenge 2013!
See the official challenge rules here: http://www.thingiverse.com/challenges/back-to-school/
description.text:
My creations:
+Test Obliterator X800 (Pencil Case)
+Eraser Thief (Pencil Topper)
+Yard Wand (Extendable/Retractable Ruler)
Pencil-reloading arm gauntlet that fits on your arm, retractable/extendable ruler that extends up to 1 yard, and a pencil topper that acts like a cookie cutter for erasers!

description.header: 100% 3D Printable. Obliterate your tests with a fresh pencil for every page!

description.text:
PENCIL CASE: The Test Obliterator X800 is a pencil-reloading arm gauntlet! Twist to eject a new pencil right into your hand! It holds 8 pencils. Never be without a writing utensil. It fits right on your arm!  
RULER: The Yard Wand is a ruler that extends to become longer - just like a wand! It can be extended to just over 3 yards. (actually, currently it lists only millimeters, and the yard wand extends to precisely 94.5cm, which is 3.1 yards!  
PENCIL TOPPER: No time for cute decorations! Does your standard pencil eraser constantly run out? Do you prefer the higher quality, fancy erasers like the MAGIC Eraser or STAEDTLER Eraser, but don't like lugging around that entire rectangle? THOSE DAYS ARE GONE, HONEY. With the Eraser Thief Pencil Topper, you can twist it through any large eraser to carve out a cylindrical eraser that fits perfectly on your pencil! Now your wooden pencil has super eraser powers!

description.header: This is 100% 3D Printable. No additional parts necessary.
WATCH THE ASSEMBLY VIDEO FOR INSTRUCTIONS: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xiYc4T6qOeo
WARNING: Scroll down and read the "Notes" section before printing. Important information regarding STL printing, left-handedness, etc.
Total PLA used ~ 0.2kg to 0.4kg (1/5 to 2/5 of a spool). -Let me know if I'm wrong, this is a best guess.

description.text:
Print the parts in the order listed (e.g. PART 01, PART 02, PART 03) and assemble. So for example, X800 Part 01 is the base. Then you stick the X800 Part 02 inside of Part 01. Then connect Part 03 on top of part 02, and so on.  
Thank you to user Barz3 who reminded me to answer questions about materials and print settings:

+I used PLA from MakerBot Industries
+I used Makerware v2.2.2.89_BETA to print everything. High/Standard/Low resolutions are standard profiles inside Makerware. I always print with my build platform heated to 40C (heated platform comes with Replicator 1 Dual and Replicator 2X), but your 3D printing techniques may vary. Almost everything was printed at low resolution, without rafts.
+Below are settings I used and approximate print times.

+PART 01 - OuterShellBottom: LOW resolution, 10 hour print time
+PART 02 - CylinderBarrelBottom: LOW resolution, 3 hour print time
+PART 03 - PencilHolder: STANDARD resolution, 30 minute print time for 1 piece NO RAFT; 1hr45min for 8 pieces (WITH RAFT to prevent any pieces getting knocked over and ruining the entire build)

description.header: I recommend you print the alternative version for thicker/larger pencils FIRST. If that fits too loosely, try the normal one.
description.text:
+PART 04 - CylinderBarrelsConnector: STANDARD resolution, 2 hour print time (LOW res is fine, but might break after several uses: 1 hour print time)
+PART 05 - OuterShellConnector: STANDARD resolution, 2 hour print time (LOW res is fine, but might break after several uses: 1 hour print time)
+PART 06 - OuterShellTop: LOW resolution, 3 hour print time
+PART 07 - CylinderBarrelTop: LOW resolution, 3 hour print time
+PART 08 - InnerShellConnector: STANDARD resolution, 2 hour print time (LOW res is fine, but might break after several uses: 1 hour print time)
+PART 09 - Final Cover: LOW resolution, 3 hour print time
+PART 10 - AccessoryHolder: STANDARD resolution, 45 minute print time
+PART 11 - AccessoryHolderInserts: HIGH resolution WITH RAFTS, 10 minute build time.

description.header: YARD WAND retractable ruler PART LIST: (6hrs)
description.text:
+ALL parts printed on LOW resolution setting without rafts.
Note: consider adding more mouse ears around the corners if you prints are peeling. I had peeling issues. +PART 01 - Main Ruler: LOW resolution, 1 hour print time
+PART 02 - Ruler 4: LOW resolution, 1 hour print time
+PART 03 - Ruler 3: LOW resolution, 1 hour print time
+PART 04 - Ruler 2: LOW resolution, 1 hour print time
+PART 05 - Ruler 1: LOW resolution, 1 hour print time
+PART 06 - Yard Wand Base: LOW resolution, 1 hour print time

description.header: ERASER THIEF Pencil Topper PART LIST:  (35 minutes)
description.text: HIGH resolution, 35 minute print time

description.header: I recommend you print the alternative version for thicker/larger pencils FIRST. If that fits too loosely, try the normal one.
Note 1: Rotate and move to build platform before printing
description.text: These STL files are NOT print-ready. In other words, you will have to use your judgment to re-orient some pieces around the X or Y axes (such as the YardWand pieces and the CylinderBarrelTop) before you can print.

description.header: Note 2: Use Sandpaper to Smooth out "X800 PART 02" for best results (optional)
description.text: For optimal results, you may want to use sandpaper to smooth out X800 PART 02 so that the pencils can slide up and down very easily. Some pencils wouldn't rise because of severe friction, but using sandpaper made it perfect.

description.header: Note 3: Different Parts for Different Pencils Sizes
description.text: The "X800 PART 03 - Pencil Holder" and the "Eraser Thief Pencil Topper" come in two versions: one for normal wooden pencils (7mm diameter, e.g. a standard Ticonderoga pencil), and a slightly enlarged version for pencils pencils (~7.5mm diameter pencils). If your pencils don't fit into the normal versions, you can print out the alternative part meant for thicker pencils!

description.header: Note 4: Right Handed v.s. Left Handed
description.text: The Outer Shell Base (X800 PART 01 ) has 4 holes on both sides. You can attach the accessory holder to either side, depending on whether you are left-handed or right-handed. I uploaded an alternative version of the base outer shell (X800 PART 01) for left-handed people!

description.header: Note 5: Don't block the pencils with the accessory connector cylinders!
description.text: The cylindrical connectors (X800 Part 11) that connect the accessory holder and outer shell base together might be a tad bit too long. Don't let them go too inside the outer shell, or they will obstruct the path of the pencils as they move along the inside. I think this part should be re-designed so that the cylinders are not allowed to go all the way through the outer shell, and so they cannot poke through the accessory holder either. (if they are poking through the front of the accessory holder, you won't be able to slide in the ruler).

(DONE)-Test Obliterator X800 Outer Shell needs a hole to allow easy reloading of pencils once you use all of them.
-An alternative Outer Shell needs to be printed for left-handed people
-The holes on the Outer Shell that allow accessories to be attached need to be modified so that connecting pieces cannot poke inside the shell and obstruct the pencils.
-The holes on the accessory holder need to be modified so that connecting pieces cannot poke through and obstruct the pathway for the ruler to slide in.
-The Yard Wand ruler should be slightly tweaked so that the ruler pieces cannot fall apart when the ruler is fully extended.
-Enable Thingiverse Customizer compatibility to auto-generate a Test Obliterator X800 based on the size of your arm.
-Enlarge Eraser Thief hole so that the pencil can fit all the way through, allowing you to raise the eraser higher as it wears away.

Hey Barz3, good question! I used PLA. Umm, after all the testing and printing, I still have PLA left. I am going to estimate that the test obliterator x800 (without extendable ruler) took up around 1/5th of a spool of plastic. Or maybe a tad bit more? I started with a brand new red PLA plastic, and after printing many parts and throwing away ones that didn't work, I still have enough PLA left so that I cannot see the inside shell of the spool (if that makes sense).
I printed everything via the standard LOW resolution preset on Makerware (no supports/rafts)
Pencil Holders (X800 Part 03) - I used standard resolution (.20mm layer height)
Eraser Thief Pencil Topper - I used highest resolution (.10mm layer height)
Attachment cylinders (X800 Part 11) - I used highest resolution
Also, to save plastic, you can choose not to print the FINAL COVER or the InnerShellConnector pieces, since they help keep everything in place if you hold the Test Obliterator X800 upside down.
I always like to heat my build platform to 40C (since I have a Replicator 1 Dual), but I figure everyone will have their own technique of printing based on what printer they have.
The parts for the YARD WAND ruler were peeling at the edges even with PLA on low resolution. I will have to try standard resolution and maybe adding more mouse ears along the corners to see if I can get the ruler to print more nicely.

description.text:
Update: After some months of use, I noticed the v5 lost some of it's shape, because PLA flexed under the growing weight of the Kossel mini (with 1kg spool on top, and pcb heatbed+4mm glass).
It still works fine, but the lower tabs now rest flat on the table, instead of being on their tips.

So I made a v6 that prints with slanted inner tab (so no more cutting needed), and I also made these a little bit thicker, to better hold the weight.
V6 is here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1597990

..

These are damper feet for the 2020 Kossel mini versions.
They are meant to be bolted to the underside of each vertical aluminum extrusion corner, so you will need to print 3 of these for a Kossel mini.

Notes:

Take care in your slicer to choose a layer width and thickness that provides lesser travel moves, this is a very simple part but some layer settings can cause more bridging and travelling moves than necessary.

It can be printed in about 15min.

These are meant to be bolted to the underside of the vertical extrusions, so you need to make an M4 thread on the vertical extrusion center hole.
While at it, I also made the same M4 threads on the top center holes, for possible later add-ons ;)

You may need to clean the hole in the feet with a drill if you want the bolt to pass freely, but I just screwed the bolt in, since the clearance is tight and it will help secure the bolt as in a nyloc nut.

Depending on your Kossel corners, you may have to cut a slight bit of the feet tab on each side (as pictured), in order for it to correctly fit in the inner side of the Kossel corner.

Designed in Blender 3d.
I tested other available snap-in designs, but they were made for 2020 extrusions, and for a Kossel mini they would have to be placed as 6 feet spreaded alongside the horizontal extrusions, and couldn't be placed at the corners (because of the Kossel's 2020 corners inner tab).

I wanted to have only 3 feet on each corner of the Kossel mini, so I made these to be bolted under each corner.

They hold up the printer very nicely and balanced, and quieter too.

title: Trefunknot, the small
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This nice little object is a soap-film (or minimal surface) connecting two knots. The trefoil knot, in the center, is one of the knots we use everyday to lace our shoes, a very simple knot (with genus one). The second one, forming the outer ring, is barely a knot. It's the infamous unknot, the most simplest knot of all, the only one having genus zero: the circle.

As a minimal surface with a boundary defined by knots, the resulting Trefunknot is a Seifert surface (named after German topologist Herbert Seifert, 1907-1996). This surface is ideal for a pendant or earrings (see my designs on Shapeways).

Under Thingiview, try to rotate the object along its vertical axis and you will see it smiling and frowning, depending on the angle.

Building the surface

Minimal surfaces are surfaces that are both constrained by some explicit property and optimized to minimize their area. Without an explicit requirement, they would just shrink to... nothing. The Trefunknot is constrained to have a trefoil knot as its internal boundary and an unknot as its external boundary.

This is however not sufficient to define it: there may be different ways (topologies) to connect these two knots. One should therefore unambiguously specify how these two curves are connected by a surface and then minimize the surface area, while satisfying the boundary constraints. Exactly as a soap film or a tensionned fabric would do naturally.

This was done using the dedicated optimization algorithms available in the open source "Surface Evolver" software.

Let's see how it works and how a Surface Evolver ".fe" file can be built for the Trefunknot.

First, we specify the two boundary knots as parametric curves, each depending therefore on one parameter "p1". The boundaries will not be part of the final surface. They are just here to indicate the place, in space, where specific parts of the surface will required to be. Both knots can be easily described using trigonometric functions. A trefoil knot with radiuses 2 and 0.9 and a circle with radius 3.2 will be used. You can change this easily. The first boundary curve will be the trefoil knot, the second will be the circle:

parameter maj_r = 2
parameter min_r = 0.9
parameter cir_r = 3.2

boundary 1 parameter 1 
x1:  min_r*sin(p1)+maj_r*sin(2*p1)
x2:  min_r*cos(p1)-maj_r*cos(2*p1)
x3:  min_r*sin(3*p1)

boundary 2 parameter 1 
x1:  cir_r*cos(p1)
x2:  cir_r*sin(p1)
x3:  0

We now need to describe how the surface having these two knots as boundary actually connects them. This is done as in most 3D modelling software using vertices (points), edges connecting pairs of vertices and faces defined by an oriented loop made from edges sharing each a vertex with the previous edge (a path).

Let's start with vertices. We will place 9 vertices on each boundary. There will be one vertex in front of each "lobe" of the trefoil and 2 intermediate vertices between them (possibly, 6 vertices could be enough). Each vertex is defined by its number, the value of the parameter that defines its position, the boundary it belongs too and possible extra flags (see Surface Evolver documentation for possible keywords here). We will use "fixed" to state that these vertices cannot be moved away from the boundary in the later optimization stage.

vertices
1    1*pi/12   boundary 1 fixed
2    4*pi/12   boundary 1 fixed
3    7*pi/12   boundary 1 fixed
4    9*pi/12   boundary 1 fixed
5    12*pi/12  boundary 1 fixed
6    15*pi/12  boundary 1 fixed
7    17*pi/12  boundary 1 fixed
8    20*pi/12  boundary 1 fixed
9    23*pi/12  boundary 1 fixed

10  -1*pi/12   boundary 2 fixed
11   2*pi/12   boundary 2 fixed
12   5*pi/12   boundary 2 fixed
13   7*pi/12   boundary 2 fixed
14   10*pi/12  boundary 2 fixed
15   13*pi/12  boundary 2 fixed
16   15*pi/12  boundary 2 fixed
17   18*pi/12  boundary 2 fixed
18   21*pi/12  boundary 2 fixed

Now, we need to create edges. The edges can be separated in three sets. The first two sets are trivial to create. They define the boundaries and therefore connects successive vertices on each boundary (vertices 1 to 9 and back to 1 on the trefoil, vertices 10 to 18 and back to 10 on the unknot). An edge is oriented (it's an arc) and is simply specified by its number, its source vertex number, its target vertex number and possible extra flags. Here, we will require that the edges shall not be movable outside of their boundary by optimization:

edges
1    1 2    boundary 1 fixed
2    2 3    boundary 1 fixed
3    3 4    boundary 1 fixed
4    4 5    boundary 1 fixed
5    5 6    boundary 1 fixed
6    6 7    boundary 1 fixed
7    7 8    boundary 1 fixed
8    8 9    boundary 1 fixed
9    9 1    boundary 1 fixed

10  10 11   boundary 2 fixed
11  11 12   boundary 2 fixed
12  12 13   boundary 2 fixed
13  13 14   boundary 2 fixed
14  14 15   boundary 2 fixed
15  15 16   boundary 2 fixed
16  16 17   boundary 2 fixed
17  17 18   boundary 2 fixed
18  18 10   boundary 2 fixed

The most challenging part remains to be done. We must now specify edges that connect non adjacent vertices. This is where a lot of choices are possible.

To get the surface below is not obvious. There is not just one topology that connects the two knots. If you need to design your own surface, you will likely need a pencil, a paper, and several sketches before entering suitable numbers here. We have 3 sets of edges connecting the two knots in facing regions and before that a set of 3 edges connecting only trefoil vertices (defining a sort of triangle in the middle, ultimately leading to a twisted hexagon using boundary edges).

19  1  6    
20  7  3    
21  4  9   

22  1  10
23  2  11
24  3  12

25  7  13
26  8  14
27  9  15

28  4  16
29  5  17
30  6  18

The last essential components of the surface are its faces. A face is defined by a succession of edges defining a path (such that each edge targets the source vertex of the next edge) and that forms a loop (the last vertex is also the first one). A face is not necessarily a triangle (it can be a n-gon) but it will be triangulated by Surface Evolver. A face is oriented and can use an edge in its original orientation or in the opposite direction. Edge 1 goes from vertex 1 to vertex 2. As a convention, edge -1 will go the other way around. Our set of oriented faces will then be defined as:

faces
1  19   6  20   3  21  9   // twisted hexagon, trefoil center
2  19  30  18 -22      
3  1   23 -10 -22
4  23  11 -24  -2
5  24  12 -25  20
6  25  13 -26  -7
7  26  14 -27  -8
8  27  15 -28  21
9  28  16 -29  -4
10 29  17 -30  -5

Finally, we specify constraints on the surface:

read
fix vertex where on_boundary 1
fix edge where on_boundary 1
fix vertex where on_boundary 2
fix edge where on_boundary 2

An image being better than all these cryptic numbers, you can see the essential topology of the unoptimized Trefunknot below, as produced by Surface Evolver using the "show" command. Not very nice yet.

Optimization of the surface

The final step is then to optimize the surface. The default criteria in Surface Evolver is to minimize the area, which is just what we need. Different optimization algorithms are available, a general subgradient algorithm and an Hessian based one (using the matrix of second partial derivatives as a guide). It is less general and used only for final optimization, when the shape is already close to optimal. We will use both.

To have an Hessian proper behavior we do:

read
hessian_normal

And then specifiy a "gogo" user procedure that will do the final optimization (why gogo ? it's just the name used by Surface Evolver's author in all his scripts for the final optimization procedure).

Surface evolver includes very useful automatic mesh refining commands:

refine edge where fixed

will allow the initial 12 edges that roughly define the boundary shapes to be refined in a larger number of edges and obtain a final results that more smoothly describes the trefoil knot and the unknot.

The "r" command refines the mesh, transforming each triangle in a set of 4 smaller triangles (as the simple subdivision surface does in Blender).

The "u" command allow to automatically change traingle to improve the meshing.

The "V" command is a vertex averaging command (much like the smooth vertex in Blender).

The "g" command is the most crucial one, It does one iteration of subgradient optimization and can be followed by a number specifying the number of iterations to perform.

Finally the "hessian" command does one iteration of Hessian (second order) optimization. This should only be used when the surface has already converged close to optimality.

The final gogo procedure can, for example, be:

// evolution
gogo := { r; g 5; refine edge where fixed; r; g 5; V 50; u 3;
               g 10; V 50; u ; hessian; r; g 50; V 50; u3 ; g 50;
               hessian; r; g 10; V 50; u 3; g 10; hessian; hessian;}

The image below shows us the final surface, after execution of one "gogo" command:

Saving to STL format

Surface evolver allows to save the final mesh as an STL file. This relies on a command that is defined in a dedicated file, which must be loaded before being executed. From the command line, one can type:

read "stl.cmd"
binary_stl >>> "Trefunknot.stl"

We now have our Trefunknot surface.

Going to 3D

Our surface is 2 dimensional and cannot be printed. We need to give it some thickness. This can be done using Blender (from blender.org). Note that SurfaceEvolver includes "thickening" commands that transforms every edge into a tube and thus printable objects. I wanted a full surface.

The STL file above can simply be imported into blender. Selecting the object and going in edit mode, one can extract the surface boundary (selecting non manifold edges, duplicating, separating to another object) and transform it into a curve. A circle of suitable thickness can then be extruded along this curve to define a round border.

Then, the "Solify" modifier is used to give the same thickness to the surface. We get our final result, which can then be 3D-printed.

I wanted a nice version of it and my Fused Filament Kossel printer was not up to my expectations. I therefore went to Shapeways and ordered an inexpensive bronze infused steel version shown below.

The bronze-infused steel version, with nice moiré effects from the fine printer slices.

It is multiplied by the nozzle size, so if your nozzle is 0.4 mm and you print with x1 shell, the wall thickness would be 0.4 mm.
That would not only make it brittle but you'll see lines where the wall is connected to the infill and most people would deem that as unfavorable.
Depend on the slicer program you use you may need to write actual thickness (aka 0.4 if that is how thick you want the wall to be) or write it as multiplier (aka 1 for example).

description.text: This is a filament guide and Dust Guard for the Thing-O-Matic.  I jut finished making a spindle for the Thing-O-Matic which left me with a need for a filament guide, but I also wanted a dust Guard, so I combined the two things into one part.  This part was design to fit on either the front or rear top of the Thing-O-Matic.  Enjoy.

• Print both sides of the part. IMPORTANT NOTE: Make sure your platform is properly calibrated as this part takes up almost the entire platform.
  • Remove the qty.4 semi-circular support section from the ID of the two parts.
  • Trim a supple sponge to roughly 25 mm in Diameter.
  • Cut a small slit in the sponge to feed the filament through.
  • using a flat surface and sandpaper, lightly sand the flat surfaces of the two parts.
  • Using a paper towel and alcohol remove any sanding debris and oils from the sanded surfaces of the parts.
  • Glue the two halves together using super glue. Secure while drying using small hobby clamps.
  • Using a razor and sandpaper clean any excess glue from the part edges.
  • Compress the sponge to force into the opening of the part. Use a then tool to reposition the sponge to the correct orientation.
  • Install on the Thing-O-Matic Top Rear or front. IMPORTANT NOTE: THE hooked end of the part should not be install on the rear vertical surface as it may interfer and damage the z-axis.
  • Run the filament through the hole in the sponge.

[edit] Minor fix to util.scad

It prints in two halves which you glue together.  
The exposed run of BB's is not held well.  Without a supermagnet behind the outside track, they'd spill out.  This means you can add BB's after gluing though!  
You may need to do some sanding to expose the BB's enough.  
You must get util.scad to use linear1.scad, it includes goodies like a proper torus primitive and much more.  Steal them to your heart's content.

description.text: This LOV1 (light, oxygen, or voltage) domain is modeled after the PDB entry 2z6c, and was manipulated visually in VMD software. LOV1 is part of the Phototropin protein, which is responsible for sensing changes in blue light,and this particular LOV1 was isolated from Arabidopsis thaliana. This print is just the A chain of the LOV1 homodimer, it is aligned asymmetrically with the B chain in "face-to-face association of the Beta-scaffolds" by a disulfide bridge and other bonds. The nucleotides that make up the active site are shown in CPK, and these nucleotides bind to a flavin mononucleotide (FMN) that absorbs blue light. The LOV1 domain in general is thought to be responsible for dimerization of Phototropin1 and Phototropin2, and regulating sensitivity to blue light activation.

description.text:
I was working on a project at home where I needed to make some 50" wide circles. I used the nail and tape on a ruler method and it worked but decided to make something more Universal and easier to use. Thus the Yardstick Compass was born! The parts slide on to any standard Yardstick to give you the ability to make any size circle from a foot to several feet wide.

I designed this is 123D design and included that .X3d file. Feel free to modify it and remix your improvements! This design is based on the use of a Sharpie but can be modified to fit other utensils like an Xacto knife or Expo Marker.

This latest version includes some oversize bolts to lock down the sliders where you would like them on the ruler. You can also use a standard sheet-rock screw as well in the center whole. You will need to cut the tip pf the screw so it does not hurt the yardstick.

The sharpie holder should be a snug fit but you may want to lock it down as well. I used a 10-32 sized nut and bolt for the latest design.

You will need supports to print this on a Makerbot or equivalent machine. I oriented them for the best print on a Makerbot with Makerbot Support. The .STL is grouped together but you can easy separate them in Meshmixer. Feel free to write me if you have any questions. :)

Happy Printing!

description.text:
I recently took up reloading and suddenly needed good ammo boxes. Of course I wanted to print them instead of buying them. Searching Thingiverse.com I came across lucassiglo21's wonderful 45ACP box which an be found here (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1078289).

I printed several and found them to be great boxes, but I wanted more. First, I wanted all my pistol caliber's to be in the same size box (9mm, 40S&W, and 45ACP). Second, I wanted the caliber to be visible from the side so I could quickly select the correct box. This wasn't strictly necessary since I print each caliber in a different color and I wanted them all to hold 50 rounds. Many smaller caliber boxes out there hold 100 rounds. Too big for me. Third, I wanted to be able to quickly generate a new box based on a new caliber without having to re-draw it. Fourth, I wanted my ammo boxes to act like a shell sorter, so that when I am collecting my brass I can reduce the number of 9MM shells that get mixed in with my 40S&W. The tolerances of these boxes are such that a 40SW shell doesn't fit easily into a 9MM box, and .380ACP is visibly too small for the box. To that end I wrote an openSCAD routine that takes casing diameter, COL, and caliber text as inputs and generates a new 50 round box with the same external dimensions (within certain round size restrictions of course). I'm not ready to post the openSCAD file yet, but here is the 9MM box. Because it has extra space, I added dividers that group the rounds in groups of 10. Nice if you are doing reloads testing different powder loads, etc. You can load up 10 rounds of each and keep track of them easily in the box. I'll post the 45ACP and .380Auto soon.

lucassiglo21's 45ACP box was the inspiration for the exterior dimensions of this box and the hing and latch design, but it isn't really a re-mix of that box because I didn't use any of his/her source files, simply measured and re-drew, but I want to make sure lucassiglo21 gets credit for a nice design from which I borrowed the hing and latch styles.

Make sure you check out the print settings for tips on getting a strong smooth print.

POST PROCESSING:
I added a small piece of support on the top latch. My printer can print it without the support, but it helps. lucassiglo21 also had support on his/her latch, but it was far too thick and was hard to remove. I made it much thinner and it doesn't seem to effect the quality of the latch and is much easier to remove. Be sure to cut it out before assembling the box.

I use a 1/16" drill bit to clean out the holes on the BOTTOM of the box and use #16 x 1 1/2" nails trimmed to the length of the hinges as the hing bering. They fit snug and last a long time.

That's it.

-Enjoy

UPDATE: If you are looking for a .223/5.56x45 box that match these boxes check out: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2177561

Notes:

My print settings are:
Material: PLA
Layer Height: 300 micron
Fill: 20% (nothing magic here. I just like the heft if gives the box. You could speed up printing by lowering the fill.
Temperature: 210 deg for the colored bottom and 215 for the clear top (makes it a little clearer).
Support: NONE (this is important or it will fill in your hinge holes. I added support where it is needed in the .STL
Raft: None

When printing the top, be sure to set your Outer Surface Parameters to 3 or greater. On my printer the default of 2 cause the thin outer walls of the top to not be filled, basically making the inner and outer wall parallel but not filled or connected. Although that gives your a nice 'clear' look in transparent white PLA, it weakens the top making it more flexible than I like. Raising the Outer Surface Parameters to 3 forces the printer to 'fill' between the two layers of the outer wall making the top strong without much decrease in transparency.

If your top seems 'flimsy' raise the Outer Surface Parameters to 3 or more.

I print the bottoms with the Outer Surface Parameters set at 2 because for some reason if I leave it set at 3 I get a rough surface to the right of the front latch, making the front of the box less attractive. Something about my printer I suppose.

Scenario:
DM: As you walk through the dimly lit tunnel, You hear the sound of snoring echo throughout the frigid ice caverns. Slowly and stealthily you approach the opening to the side cavern from which the baritone sounds of slumber emanate. As you peek around the corner you see a huge cavern sparsely furnished with primitive table and chairs that look to be fashioned from rough logs lashed together. Lying beside the table and an overturned chair you see the source of the snoring. The blue body of a 2500 lb 22 ft tall frost giant sleeps in an awkward twisted position suggesting that he drank himself to sleep and fell out of his chair. A barrel of what is probably an alcoholic beverage is still clutched in his left hand and his gargantuan double bladed ax lies across his chest held tightly in his right. The room could easily be passed and the giant ignored except your eyes are drawn to an elaborate treasure chest easily eight feet tall. You begin to wonder if giants have giant gold pieces, giant gems, and giant magical treasures.

Group: We sneak past the giant and inspect the chest for traps

DM: OK evil grin

This mimic is sized to about 42mm tall, but can easily be scaled down to a more common size.

This is a drawing attachment for the Makergear M2 Printer.

First the Disclaimer........

This is a work in progress (I am uploading this per request.)

This attachment is NOT for the average user. It requires advanced knowledge of the M2 printer such as moving and calibrating your Z-stop. It also requires advanced g-code editing and slicer setting to make work...

If you are not an advanced printer user and don't know what your doing please do not try to use this... I make no guarantees or warranties as to the accuracy or completeness of, or results to be obtained from accessing and using the Information herein.

With all that being said........

Videos are speed up 4X-6X
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N9RF_GtY0rE
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c-wAcamFsb4

Hardware Required = Five M3x8 screws

The Filament mount is removed and swapped with the scribbler attachment.

I don't have time to write up full instructions but some tidbits for now....

Line drawing were taking from google and converted to an SVG and then imported into tinkercad to convert to a STL (see http://3dprinting.com.au/converting-images-into-3d-models/)

There are two mount inserts one fits a standard sharpie and one for a fine tip sharpie. (Sanding might be required to fit the markers.) To use the markers I move (slide up) my entire z-stop bracket and switch to keep the hotend away from the bed.

To set the marker height I start the drawing and then hit stop (in program) while holding the z-stop knob from moving to keep the bed at the right height. I then insert the marker in the mount until it hits the paper and lock the insert in place with the front M3 screw.

(I use Simplify3d) To get the printer to start you need to add the M302 command to the starting scrip. I remove a lot of the commands in the starting scrip (whip commands, purge, ect) I also add around 5mm of Retraction Vertical Lift (extruder tab) so it picks up the drawing tool when moving.

The pen insert uses a cartridge and spring from a G2 gel pen. The spring is inserted in first then the pen cartridge. (opposite of how it is in the pen) This makes it spring loaded so it will draw on the paper better. (the 5mm of Retraction Vertical Lift is important to have if your printer starts off the build plate or the pen will hit the build surface on the first move.)

I set the layer height .1 and then the stop printing height the same (advance tab) so it only draws one layer, the top and bottom layers are set to 0 and outline shell to 1. I play around with the extrusion multiplier and preview window until a get a single line for everything (depends on the file used) I use 100% infill if I want to color in between the lines. (the skull pictures shows with and with out infill.)

That's all I have time/motivation for right now......
